DTSTART;VALUE=DATE;VALUE=DATE:20250909
CLASS:PUBLIC
DESCRIPTION:Unit 1 Progress\n\nIcon Progress Bar/Navigation (built in brows
 er\, hidden in app)\n\n \n\n---------\nOBJECTIVE\n---------\n\nThe object
 ive of this project is for students to acquire and display results from re
 ading both structured and unstructured data from various sources\, includi
 ng raw files\, SQL databases\, online repositories\, and programmatically 
 through the use of APIs. This project aims to help students understand how
  to ingest data from diverse sources\, focusing primarily on using the pan
 das library to interact with the data. Students will retrieve data from di
 fferent sources\, comprehend the differences between data types\, and beco
 me familiar with Jupyter notebooks\, a key tool for data science.\n\nKey F
 ocus Areas:\n\n* Using Jupyter notebooks for data acquisition\n\n* Utilizi
 ng pandas\, SQL\, and other important libraries to acquire data\n\n* Under
 standing the differences between structured\, unstructured\, time series\,
  and real-time data\n\n* Recognizing the differences between primary and s
 econdary data sources\n\n------------\nINSTRUCTIONS\n------------\n\nDownl
 oad and use this [Jupyter Notebook Starter File] (https://elearning.mines.
 edu/courses/76742/files/8063903?wrap=1) for your solutions to the tasks be
 low. Please complete all of your work for this project in the same Jupyter
  Notebook file\, which you will submit.\n\nPart 1: Structured Data\n------
 -----------------\n\nData can be ingested in many different ways\, Pandas 
 offers a lot of ways to load data\, see https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/ref
 erence/io.html \n\nPickling\n\nFlat File \n\nClipbard\n\nExcel\n\nJSON\n
 \nHTML\n\nXML\n\nLatex\n\nHDF5\n\nFeather\n\nParquet\n\nORC\n\nSAS\n\nSPSS
 \n\nSQL\n\nBigQuery\n\nSTATA\n\n ... \n\nTASK: Your task is to read seve
 ral different file types using pandas (e.g.\, csv\, text\, json\, database
 ) and learn about some pandas functionalities to display the loaded data. 
 Instructions for each are provided below.\n\nCSV\n---\n\nCSV File Acquisit
 ion\n--------------------\n\n* Load csv data from the provided data_url be
 low\, using pandas into a dataframe\n\ndata_url = "https://archive.ics.uci
 .edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/wine-quality/winequality-red.csv"\n\n* 
 Print the dataframe's first few elements using the .head() command to se
 e what data you have\n\n* Change the names of the columns\, using [df.rena
 me](https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.rename.h
 tml)\n\n* Try this with inplace=true\n\n* Try again without inplace=true b
 ut make sure to resave the dataframe\n\n* Print the tail of the dataframe 
 using the .tail() command\n\nText (TXT)\n----------\n\nTXT File Acquisitio
 n\n--------------------\n\n* Load [employees.txt] (https://elearning.mines
 .edu/courses/76742/files/8063931?wrap=1) in using pandas into a dataframe\
 n\n* Print the dataframe's first few elements using the .head() command 
 to see what data you have\n\n* Using the info\, describe\, value_counts\, 
 and groupby functions in pandas\, please answer the following questions\n\
 n* How many entries and columns are there in the dataset?\n\n* What is the
  average age and average salary of the employees in the dataset?\n\n* Whic
 h occupation has the highest number of employees?\n\n* What is the average
  salary for each occupation\, and which occupation has the highest average
  salary?\n\nJSON\n----\n\nJSON File Acquisition\n---------------------\n\n
 * Load the [movies.json] (https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/
 8063757?wrap=1) file using pandas into a dataframe\n\n* Print the datafram
 e's first few elements using the .head() command to see what data you ha
 ve\n\n* Use the isna() function to get a count of how many missing values 
 there are in the dataframe\n\n* Use the sample() function to understand it
 s use\n\nDatabase\n--------\n\nDatabase Acquisition (OPTIONAL for Advanced
  Users)\n--------------------------------------------------\n\n* Load the 
 [employees.db] (https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/8063744?wr
 ap=1) in using pandas read_sql() function and store in a dataframe\n\n* Pr
 int the dataframe's first few elements using the .head() command to see 
 what data you have\n\n* Perform SQL queries to find the following informat
 ion:\n\n* Number of unique departments\n\n* Average salary\n\n* Number of 
 employees\n\n* Who are the employees in the engineering department?\n\nPar
 t 2: Unstructured Data\n-------------------------\n\nData can be provided 
 in various formats\, with some examples beyond structured data being:\n\n*
  Sometimes\, you may need to access data held by another company. The best
  approach is to use an API to request the company's data services\, which 
 will return the necessary data.\n\n* Sometimes\, you may need to work with
  an entire directory of files. The best approach is to loop through the di
 rectory and read each file.\n\nTASK: Your task is to practice using an API
  and reading a directory of text files to extract information. Detailed in
 structions for each method are provided below.\n\nAPIs\n----\n\nApplicatio
 n Programming Interfaces (mini project)\n---------------------------------
 ----------------\n\nWe will practice connecting to the SpaceX API and see
  what information we can get back!\n\n* Connect to the SpaceX API - Set up
  a connection to the SpaceX API. We can use the requests library to connec
 t to the SpaceX API by specifying the API endpoint URL.\nMore info at: htt
 ps://docs.spacexdata.com/ \n\n* Retrieve Data on Past Launches - Fetch da
 ta on past launches from the SpaceX API. We can use the requests.get() met
 hod to send a GET request to the SpaceX API endpoint and use the .json() m
 ethod to parse the response.\n\n* Load Data into a Pandas DataFrame - Load
  the retrieved data into a Pandas DataFrame.\n\n* Perform Basic Data Analy
 sis - Perform basic data analysis on the retrieved data. We can use the de
 scribe() and info() methods to get basic statistics and information about 
 the DataFrame.\n\n* Filter Data Based on Launch Success - Filter the data 
 to find only successful launches. We can use boolean indexing to filter th
 e DataFrame for rows where the success column is True.\n\n* Group Data by 
 Year - Note\, use the column "date_utc" in your dataset. Group the data by
  year and count the number of launches each year. We can use the pd.to_dat
 etime() method to convert the date column to datetime\, extract the year u
 sing the .dt.year accessor\, and use the groupby() method to group the dat
 a by year and count the number of launches.\n\nDirectory of Files\n-------
 -----------\n\nReading a Directory of Files\n----------------------------\
 n\n* Since we did not cover this\, you will be provided the code to proces
 s of working with a directory of data. We will use a collection of text da
 ta (movie reviews) to demonstrate how to load\, process\, and analyze unst
 ructured text data.\n\n* Load Text Data from Files - See if you can setup 
 the 'reviews' directory and read the three given text files (e.g.\, [revie
 w1.txt] (https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/8063812?wrap=1)\,
  [review2.txt] (https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/8063901?wr
 ap=1)\, [review3.txt] (https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/806
 3926?wrap=1)). To load the data\, we have to use typical python file loadi
 ng.\n\n* We will need the os package and have to loop through our files to
  find all .txt files.\n\n* Once we find them\, we will load them into an a
 rray for storage.\n\n* And print them out to make sure we got all the file
 s!\n\n* As a stretch goal\, modify the code and see if you can read other 
 types of files.\n\n------------------------\nSUBMITTING YOUR SOLUTION\n---
 ---------------------\n\nSubmit your notebook file. To submit your noteboo
 k\, first clear all the cells (this won't matter too much this time\, but 
 for larger data sets in the future\, it will make the file smaller). Then 
 use the File->Download As->Notebook to obtain the notebook file. Finally\,
  submit the notebook file(s) with your solutions to Canvas.
SEQUENCE:0
