CLASS:PUBLIC
DESCRIPTION:---------------------------------------------------------------
 -------------------------\nLinear and Quadratic Discriminant Analysis - do
 es it get any more complicated than that?\n-------------------------------
 ---------------------------------------------------------\n\nLDA and QDA a
 re conceptually challenging methods and rely quite heavily on the assumpti
 on of normality of the predictor variables. While they are powerful method
 s in the right setting\, you want to carefully check these assumptions whe
 n applying these methods in your work.\n\n* Explain the goals of LDA and Q
 DA. What do these two methods have in common and what is different?\n\n* S
 elect a publicly available dataset (a good source is https://catalog.data.
 gov/dataset?q=&sort=views_recent+desc) and analyze the data using LDA or Q
 DA. Discuss your results and include plots or graphics. Be sure to mention
  whether the assumptions for these methods were met\, which features you c
 hose to analyze\, and what the results were.\n\n* What role does sample si
 ze play in your decision to use QDA vs LDA? Discuss this question in the c
 ontext of number of parameters to estimate and how you would go about maki
 ng the call which methods to use in your work.\n\n \n\nPost your thoughts
  to the questions above and provide constructive feedback to at least two 
 (2) of your peers.\n\nYou will in turn receive feedback from your colleagu
 es and instructors\, and have until EOD Sunday to address the feedback you
  receive from your colleagues and instructors before your discussion post 
 will be graded.\n\nEstimated time requirement: 4 hours
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Module 4 | Discussion [Fall 2025.MATH561A.81045]
URL;VALUE=URI:https://elearning.mines.edu/calendar?include_contexts=course_
 75552&month=09&year=2025#assignment_506609
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://instructu
 re-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com/account_98020000000000001/attachments/7108468/
 dp_app3.css"><h2>Linear and Quadratic Discriminant Analysis - does it get 
 any more complicated than that?</h2>\n<p>LDA and QDA are conceptually chal
 lenging methods and rely quite heavily on the assumption of normality of t
 he predictor variables. While they are powerful methods in the right setti
 ng\, you want to carefully check these assumptions when applying these met
 hods in your work.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Explain the goals of LDA and QDA. What d
 o these two methods have in common and what is different?</li>\n<li>Select
  a publicly available dataset (a good source is https://catalog.data.gov/d
 ataset?q=&amp\;sort=views_recent+desc) and analyze the data using LDA or Q
 DA. Discuss your results and include plots or graphics. Be sure to mention
  whether the assumptions for these methods were met\, which features you c
 hose to analyze\, and what the results were.</li>\n<li>What role does samp
 le size play in your decision to use QDA vs LDA? Discuss this question in 
 the context of number of parameters to estimate and how you would go about
  making the call which methods to use in your work.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp\
 ;</p>\n<p>Post your thoughts to the questions above and provide constructi
 ve feedback to at least two (2) of your peers.</p>\n<p>You will in turn re
 ceive feedback from your colleagues and instructors\, and have until EOD S
 unday to address the feedback you receive from your colleagues and instruc
 tors before your discussion post will be graded.</p>\n<p><strong>Estimated
  time requirement: 4 hours</strong></p><script src="https://instructure-up
 loads.s3.amazonaws.com/account_98020000000000001/attachments/7108467/dp_ap
 p%20%25281%2529.js"></script>
END:VEVENT
