DESCRIPTION:---------------------------------------\nTo prune or not - that
  is the question!\n---------------------------------------\n\nTree-pruning
  is an important step in using decision trees when analyzing data you will
  encounter in your career.\n\n* The approach to decision trees described i
 n the book is a greedy approach. Explain what is meant by the term "greedy
 ". Describe why this algorithm to build trees does not always arrive at a 
 globally optimal tree.\n\n* Discuss the specific results in Figure 8.5. Ar
 e they what you would have expected?\n\n* Explain the limitations of recur
 sive binary splitting. This is a nonlinear method\, so will it always outp
 erform a linear method on nonlinear data? Why or why not?\n\n* Imagine you
  are a consultant working on the baseball salary data from your text book.
  Would you rather show your clients Figure 8.1 or Figure 8.4? What motivat
 es your choice\, and how would you go about explaining your choice to your
  client?\n\n \n\nPost your thoughts to the questions above and provide co
 nstructive feedback to at least two (2) of your peers.\n\nYou will in turn
  receive feedback from your colleagues and instructors\, and have until EO
 D Sunday to address the feedback you receive from your colleagues and inst
 ructors before your discussion post will be graded.\n\nEstimated time requ
 irement: 3 hours
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Module 5 | Discussion [Fall 2025.MATH561A.81045]
URL;VALUE=URI:https://elearning.mines.edu/calendar?include_contexts=course_
 75552&month=09&year=2025#assignment_506610
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://instructu
 re-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com/account_98020000000000001/attachments/7108468/
 dp_app3.css"><h2>To prune or not - that is the question!</h2>\n<p>Tree-pru
 ning is an important step in using decision trees when analyzing data you 
 will encounter in your career.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The approach to decision tre
 es described in the book is a greedy approach. Explain what is meant by th
 e term "greedy". Describe why this algorithm to build trees does not alway
 s arrive at a globally optimal tree.</li>\n<li>Discuss the specific result
 s in Figure 8.5. Are they what you would have expected?</li>\n<li>Explain 
 the limitations of recursive binary splitting. This is a nonlinear method\
 , so will it always outperform a linear method on nonlinear data? Why or w
 hy not?</li>\n<li>Imagine you are a consultant working on the baseball sal
 ary data from your text book. Would you rather show your clients Figure 8.
 1 or Figure 8.4? What motivates your choice\, and how would you go about e
 xplaining your choice to your client?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp\;</p>\n<p>Post
  your thoughts to the questions above and provide constructive feedback to
  at least two (2) of your peers.</p>\n<p>You will in turn receive feedback
  from your colleagues and instructors\, and have until EOD Sunday to addre
 ss the feedback you receive from your colleagues and instructors before yo
 ur discussion post will be graded.</p>\n<p><strong>Estimated time requirem
 ent: 3 hours</strong></p><script src="https://instructure-uploads.s3.amazo
 naws.com/account_98020000000000001/attachments/7108467/dp_app%20%25281%252
 9.js"></script>
END:VEVENT
