DESCRIPTION:Unit 2 Progress\n\nIcon Progress Bar/Navigation (built in brows
 er\, hidden in app)\n\n \n\n---------\nOBJECTIVE\n---------\n\nThe object
 ive of this project is for students to preprocess acquired structured and 
 unstructured datasets to transform raw data into a format suitable for mac
 hine learning algorithms. This includes feature extraction\, removal of er
 roneous or redundant data\, and outliers. Students will also practice expl
 oratory data analysis and visualization techniques to examine patterns\, r
 elationships\, and outliers in their data.\n\nKey Focus Areas:\n\n* Utiliz
 e key pandas functions like describe\, info\, and matplotlib to understand
  the data.\n\n* Practice cleaning the data by replacing missing values\, n
 ormalizing\, and using PCA to transform the dataset.\n\n* Once the dataset
  is prepared\, use train_test_split to ready it for modeling.\n\n* Additio
 nally\, work briefly with unstructured data to clean and prepare it for mo
 deling.\n\n------------\nINSTRUCTIONS\n------------\n\nDownload and use th
 is [Jupyter Notebook Starter File] (https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/7
 6742/files/8063734?wrap=1)[ Download Jupyter Notebook Starter File] (http
 s://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/8063903/download)for your solu
 tions to the tasks below. Please complete all of your work for this projec
 t in the same Jupyter Notebook file\, which you will submit.\n\nPart 1: St
 ructured Data\n-----------------------\n\nTASK: Complete the following ste
 ps (1 - 8) to work with data from a CSV file and perform a series of prepr
 ocessing tasks. These tasks will help you solidify your understanding by g
 enerating basic and advanced descriptive statistics\, conducting explorato
 ry data analysis\, handling missing values and outliers\, and practicing d
 ata scaling and reduction techniques.\n\nNote: For each step\, we have pro
 vided recommended activities along with some optional ones to practice pre
 processing. If you discover additional or alternative experiments\, feel f
 ree to include them in your analysis.\n\nSteps 1 and 2\n-------------\n\nS
 tep 1: Setup\n-------------\n\n* Load Libraries and Data: Import the neces
 sary libraries into your Python environment\n\n* Load the [flights-small.c
 sv] (https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/8063924?wrap=1) datas
 et using Pandas into a dataframe\n\n* Print the dataframe's first few elem
 ents using the .head() command to see what data you have\n\nStep 2: Descr
 iptive Statistics\n------------------------------\n\nGenerate Basic Descri
 ptive Statistics:\n\n* Use Pandas to display basic information about the d
 ataset\, such as data types\, number of non-null values\, and memory usage
 .\n\n* Generate summary statistics including mean\, median\, standard devi
 ation\, minimum\, and maximum values for each numerical column.\n\nAdvance
 d Descriptive Statistics (optional):\n\n* Calculate additional statistics 
 such as skewness and kurtosis to understand the distribution and shape of 
 the data using the following df functions:\n\ndf.skew()\ndf.kurtosis()\n\n
 Note\, you will likely have to convert some columns to numerical OR limit 
 columns to be used using something like the below sample code:\n\ndf.selec
 t_dtypes(include=np.number)\nOR\nnumerical_cols = ["col1"\, "col2"\, ...]\
 ndf[numerical_cols].skew()\ndf[numerical_cols].kurtosis()\n\n* More option
 al extras:\n\n* Generate a correlation matrix to identify relationships be
 tween numerical features. Visualize the matrix using a heatmap.\n\n* To ge
 nerate a correlation matrix\, you can use df.corr(). You may need to use t
 he same code as above to limit which columns are used.\n\nSteps 3 and 4\n-
 ------------\n\nStep 3: Exploratory Data Visualization\n------------------
 --------------------\n\nVisualize Distributions:\n\nCreate box plots to id
 entify the presence of outliers in numerical features.\n\nVisualize Relati
 onships:\n\n* Use scatter plots to visualize the relationship between pair
 s of numerical features.\n\n* Use heatmaps to visualize the correlation ma
 trix\, showing the strength of relationships between features.\n\nVisualiz
 e Categorical Features:\n\n* Use count plots to visualize the frequency of
  categories in categorical features.\n\n* Create bar plots to compare the 
 mean or sum of numerical features across different categories.\n\nStep 4: 
 Data Cleansing\n----------------------\n\nData Selection:\n\nFor this step
 \, you will need to split the columns into numerical and non-numerical to 
 apply the transformations appropriately\, to do this use the following lis
 ts\, then when applying transformations use the appropriate list:\n\nnumer
 ical_columns = [\n    'year'\, 'month'\, 'day'\, 'dep_time'\, 'sched_dep
 _time'\, \n    'dep_delay'\, 'arr_time'\, 'sched_arr_time'\, 'arr_delay
 '\, \n  'flight'\, 'air_time'\, 'distance'\, 'hour'\, 'minute' ]\n\nnon_
 numerical_columns = [\n  'carrier'\, 'tailnum'\, 'origin'\, 'dest'\, 'tim
 e_hour'\, 'name' ]\n\nHandle Missing Values:\n\n* Identify columns with mi
 ssing values using Pandas.\n\n* Handle missing values by either filling th
 em with appropriate statistics (mean\, median\, mode) or by removing rows/
 columns with missing values.\n\n* Handle missing categorical values by fil
 ling with the mode\n\n.fillna(df[column].mode()[0])\n\nHandle Outliers:\n\
 n* Identify outliers using visualizations like box plots.\n\n* Remove outl
 iers using statistical methods like the IQR (Interquartile Range) method o
 r use more advanced techniques like Isolation Forest from Scikit-learn for
  outlier detection.\n\nSteps 5 and 6\n-------------\n\nStep 5: Data Transf
 ormation\n---------------------------\n\nNormalize or Standardize Numerica
 l Features:\n\nNormalize or standardize numerical features to bring them o
 nto a common scale using Scikit-learn's StandardScaler or MinMaxScaler.\n\
 nEncode Categorical Features:\n\n* Convert categorical features into numer
 ical values using encoding techniques.\n\n* Use one-hot encoding for nomin
 al categorical features with no ordinal relationship.\n\n* Use label encod
 ing for ordinal categorical features.\n\nApply Custom Transformations:\n\n
 Apply custom transformations to features if required\, such as log transfo
 rmations or polynomial feature generation.\n\nStep 6: Dimensionality Reduc
 tion\n--------------------------------\n\nApply PCA to Reduce Dimensionali
 ty:\n\n* Use Principal Component Analysis (PCA) from Scikit-learn to reduc
 e the number of features while retaining most of the variance in the data.
 \n\n* Determine the number of principal components to retain by examining 
 the explained variance ratio.\n\nAdvanced Dimensionality Reduction Techniq
 ues (optional):\n\n* Explore other dimensionality reduction techniques lik
 e Kernel PCA\, t-SNE\, or LDA if the data has complex relationships or non
 -linear patterns.\n\nSteps 7 and 8\n-------------\n\nStep 7: Data Balancin
 g\, Merging\, Aggregation\n--------------------------------------------\n\
 nAggregate Data:\n\n* Aggregate data to summarize it by certain features u
 sing group-by operations in Pandas.\n\n* Calculate aggregate statistics li
 ke mean\, sum\, count\, etc.\, to generate summarized views of the data.\n
 \nStep 8: Data Splitting (Train\, Test\, Validate)\n----------------------
 ------------------------\n\nSplit Data into Training\, Testing\, and Valid
 ation Sets:\n\n* Split the dataset into training\, testing\, and validatio
 n sets using Scikit-learn's train_test_split function.\n\n* Typically\, al
 locate 70-80% of the data for training\, 20-30% for testing\, and optional
 ly\, 10-20% for validation.\n\n* Ensure that the splits are representative
  of the overall dataset distribution.\n\nPart 2: Unstructured Data\n------
 -------------------\n\nTASK: In this task\, you will clean and preprocess
  the text data using several steps. You will start by removing punctuation
 \, converting text to lowercase\, tokenizing the data\, and removing stop 
 words. After preprocessing (using the provided sample code)\, you will app
 ly TF-IDF to the cleaned data and display the results.\n\n* Use the provid
 ed code and sample data as a starting place\n\n* Run the code and print ou
 t the reviews list to ensure you are ready to clean and preprocess the t
 ext data\n\n* Remove Punctuation: Use the nltk package to remove punctuati
 on from the text data.\n\n* Convert to Lowercase: Convert all text to lowe
 rcase using the lower() function.\n\n* Tokenize the Data: Tokenize the tex
 t data to break it down into individual words or tokens.\n\n* Remove Stop 
 Words: Remove any stop words from the text to focus on the meaningful word
 s.\n\n------------------------\nSUBMITTING YOUR SOLUTION\n----------------
 --------\n\nSubmit your notebook file. To submit your notebook\, first cle
 ar all the cells (this won't matter too much this time\, but for larger da
 ta sets in the future\, it will make the file smaller). Then use the File-
 >Download As->Notebook to obtain the notebook file. Finally\, submit the n
 otebook file(s) with your solutions to Canvas.
