DESCRIPTION:----------------------------------------------\nRandom Forest a
 nd Boosting - the How and When!\n-----------------------------------------
 -----\n\nRandom Forest and Boosting are two key methodologies we often use
  in practice. You want to have a clear picture in your mind what their str
 ength and weaknesses are when making decisions on whether to use them in y
 our work.\n\n* Can you draw parallels between decision trees\, random fore
 sts and boosting to human decision making and/or machine learning methods 
 such as neural networks? Can you identify some key differences?\n\n* What 
 exactly is meant by learning slowly in boosting? Explain it in the larger 
 context of how boosting works.\n\n* Generally speaking Random Forest and B
 oosting clearly outperform individual decision trees in terms of predictio
 n accuracy. Why would you still want to consider using decision-trees in p
 ractical scenarios? Give a specific example of a situation where you have 
 or or would opt for individual decision trees. Can be something you have e
 ncountered in your work or a hypothetical example. In the latter case we w
 ant a good story! :)\n\n \n\nPost your thoughts to the questions above an
 d provide constructive feedback to at least two (2) of your peers.\n\nYou 
 will in turn receive feedback from your colleagues and instructors\, and h
 ave until EOD Sunday to address the feedback you receive from your colleag
 ues and instructors before your discussion post will be graded.\n\n \n\nE
 stimated time requirement: 3 hours
