 lor: #ffffff\;">Random Forest and Boosting are two key methodologies we of
 ten use in practice. You want to have a clear picture in your mind what th
 eir strength and weaknesses are when making decisions on whether to use th
 em in your work.<br></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Can you draw parallels between 
 decision trees\, random forests and boosting to human decision making and/
 or machine learning methods such as neural networks? Can you identify some
  key differences?</li>\n<li>What exactly is meant by <em>learning slowly</
 em> in boosting? Explain it in the larger context of how boosting works.</
 li>\n<li>Generally speaking Random Forest and Boosting clearly outperform 
 individual decision trees in terms of prediction accuracy. Why would you s
 till want to consider using decision-trees in practical scenarios? Give a 
 specific example of a situation where you have or or would opt for individ
 ual decision trees. Can be something you have encountered in your work or 
 a hypothetical example. In the latter case we want a good story! :)</li>\n
 </ul>\n<p>&nbsp\;</p>\n<p>Post your thoughts to the questions above and pr
 ovide constructive feedback to at least two (2) of your peers.</p>\n<p>You
  will in turn receive feedback from your colleagues and instructors\, and 
