DESCRIPTION:---------------------------------------------------------------
 -------\nMaximal margin and support vector classifiers - linear boundary i
 t is!\n-------------------------------------------------------------------
 ---\n\nMaximal margin and support vector classifiers form the foundation o
 f support vector machines. They rely on the concept of a linear boundary t
 o separate classes\, which is rarely present with real data\, but can be a
  useful approximation.\n\n* Explain the conceptual difference between a ma
 ximal margin classifier and a support vector classifier. Use Fig. 9.6 in y
 our exposition.\n\n* Provide an application where you would expect a suppo
 rt vector classifier to be necessary\, and one where a maximal margin clas
 sifier would be sufficient. Explain your reasoning. \n\n* Compare the sup
 port vector classifier to other methods of classification discussed in thi
 s class. What are its advantages and disadvantages?\n\n* Discuss our favor
 ite subject\, the bias-variance trade-off\, in the context of support vect
 or classifiers.\n\n \n\nPost your thoughts to the questions above and pro
 vide constructive feedback to at least two (2) of your peers.\n\nYou will 
 in turn receive feedback from your colleagues and instructors\, and have u
 ntil EOD Sunday to address the feedback you receive from your colleagues a
 nd instructors before your discussion post will be graded.\n\nEstimated ti
 me requirement: 3 hours
