 undary it is!</h2>\n<p>Maximal margin and support vector classifiers form 
 the foundation of support vector machines. They rely on the concept of a l
 inear boundary to separate classes\, which is rarely present with real dat
 a\, but can be a useful approximation.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Explain the conceptu
 al difference between a maximal margin classifier and a support vector cla
 ssifier. Use Fig. 9.6 in your exposition.</li>\n<li>Provide an application
  where you would expect a support vector classifier to be necessary\, and 
 one where a maximal margin classifier would be sufficient. Explain your re
 asoning.&nbsp\;</li>\n<li>Compare the support vector classifier to other m
