 ile</span></a></span>for your solutions to the tasks below. Please complet
 e all of your work for this project in the same Jupyter Notebook file\, wh
 ich you will submit.</p>\n<h3>The Dataset</h3>\n<p><strong>Dataset Selecti
 on: </strong>You will be using the Bike Sharing dataset\, which includes v
 arious attributes related to bike rental counts in a city. This dataset is
  unique and provides a real-world application for predicting the number of
  bike rentals. You can access the data from the below URL or download this
  file (<a class="instructure_file_link inline_disabled" title="day.csv" hr
 ef="https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/8063930?wrap=1" target
 ="_blank" data-api-endpoint="https://elearning.mines.edu/api/v1/courses/76
 742/files/8063930" data-api-returntype="File">day.csv</a>) and adjust the 
 starter code provided in the notebook file.</p>\n<pre>url = "https://archi
 ve.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/00275/Bike-Sharing-Dataset.zi
 p"</pre>\n<p><strong>Dataset Description:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Bike
  Sharing dataset contains (one with 17\,379 instances and one with 731 ins
 tances and approx. 16 features)\, such as date\, temperature\, humidity\, 
 wind speed\, and more.</li>\n<li>The target variable is the count of total
  rentals on each day.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Data Preprocessing Suggestions</h3>
 \n<p><strong>Loading Data:</strong> Load the Bike Sharing dataset using Pa
 ndas.</p>\n<p><strong>Data Exploration and Visualization:</strong> Produce
  some visualizations\, statistics\, etc. to gain an understanding for the 
 dataset and what it contains.</p>\n<p><strong>Handling Missing Values:</st
 rong> Check for and handle any missing values in the dataset (if any).</p>
 \n<p><strong>Encoding Categorical Variables:</strong> Convert categorical 
 variables to numerical values using techniques like one-hot encoding (if a
 ny you see that need this).</p>\n<p><strong>Feature Engineering:</strong> 
 Create new features from the date column (e.g.\, day of the week\, month\,
  hour) to capture temporal patterns.</p>\n<p><strong>Standardization:</str
 ong> Standardize the features to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation
  of 1 for consistent training. This step helps ensure that the model is no
 t biased towards features with larger scales.</p>\n<p><strong>Train-Test S
 plit: </strong>Split the dataset into training and testing sets to evaluat
 e the model's performance on unseen data.</p>\n<h3>Building the Model</h3>
 \n<p><strong>Model Initialization:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Choosing Hyperp
 arameters: Explain key hyperparameters such as the fit_intercept and n_job
 s.</li>\n<li>Linear Regression Initialization: Use the LinearRegression cl
 ass from Scikit-learn\, specifying the chosen hyperparameters.</li>\n</ul>
 \n<p><strong>Model Fitting:</strong> Fit the Linear Regression model to th
 e standardized Bike Sharing dataset.</p>\n<h3>Evaluating the Model</h3>\n<
 p><strong>Performance Metrics: </strong>Calculate metrics such as Mean Abs
 olute Error (MAE)\, Mean Squared Error (MSE)\, Root Mean Squared Error (RM
 SE)\, and R-squared (R2) to evaluate the model. These metrics provide insi
 ghts into the model’s predictive performance and its ability to generali
 ze.</p>\n<hr style="color: #92a2bd\; border: 1px solid\;">\n<h2 class="p1"
 >SUBMITTING YOUR SOLUTION</h2>\n<p class="p1">Submit your notebook file. T
