DTSTART;VALUE=DATE;VALUE=DATE:20251103
CLASS:PUBLIC
DESCRIPTION:Unit 3 Part 2 Progress\n\nIcon Progress Bar/Navigation (built i
 n browser\, hidden in app)\n\n \n\n---------\nOBJECTIVE\n---------\n\nThe
  objective of this project is to introduce students to the concepts of Gau
 ssian Mixture Models (GMMs) and provide hands-on experience in implementin
 g them using Python's Scikit-learn library. Students will learn how to pre
 process data\, build\, fit\, and evaluate a GMM\, and understand the signi
 ficance of various parameters and their impact on the model's performance.
 \n\nNOTE: Even though Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM) is an unsupervised lea
 rning method\, when applied to anomaly detection\, it can be treated simil
 arly to a supervised task. After training the GMM on normal data\, we can 
 use a train-test split to evaluate its performance on new data. The model 
 assigns probabilities to each point\, and by setting a threshold on these 
 probabilities\, we can classify points as either normal or anomalous. This
  allows us to evaluate the model using traditional classification metrics 
 like precision\, recall\, and the F1-score\, just as we would in a supervi
 sed classification task.\n\n------------\nINSTRUCTIONS\n------------\n\nDo
 wnload and use this [Jupyter Notebook Starter File] (https://elearning.mi
 nes.edu/courses/76742/files/8063820?wrap=1) for your solutions to the task
 s below. Please complete all of your work for this project in the same Jup
 yter Notebook file\, which you will submit.\n\nThe Dataset\n-----------\n\
 nDataset Selection: You will be using the The Credit Card Fraud Detection 
 dataset for the project to implement an experiment in anomaly detection. Y
 ou can access the data from this file ([creditcard.csv] (https://elearning
 .mines.edu/courses/76742/files/8063759?wrap=1)). \n\nDataset Description:
 \n\n* Real-World Dataset: The Credit Card Fraud Detection dataset which in
 cludes various features of transactions and a binary label indicating frau
 d.\n\n* Note: If the dataset loading is slow / running crashes\, change yo
 ur dataset to use a subset of the data.\n\ndf_subset = df[:1000]\n\nData P
 reprocessing\n------------------\n\nLoading Data: Load the Credit Card Fra
 ud Detection dataset using Pandas. Review the data using .info()\, .descri
 be()\, etc. \n\nHandling Missing Values: Identify and handle any missing 
 values in the dataset (e.g.\, using mean or median imputation). This is KE
 Y\, the GMM model cannot accept data with missing data points.\n\nFeature 
 Scaling: Standardize the features to have a mean of 0 and a standard devia
 tion of 1 for consistent training.\n\nSeparate the Target: The target of t
 his dataset is “Class”\, please ensure you remove it from the dataset.
 \n\nTrain-Test Split: Split the dataset into training and testing sets to
  evaluate the model's performance on unseen data.\n\nBuilding the Model\n-
 -----------------\n\nModel Initialization:\n\n* Number of Components: Deci
 de on the number of Gaussian components (clusters) to use.\n\n* Covariance
  Type: Choose the type of covariance matrix (e.g.\, full\, tied\, diagonal
 \, spherical).\n\nModel Fitting: Fit the GMM to the features of the real-w
 orld dataset for anomaly detection.\n\nEvaluating the Model\n-------------
 -------\n\nPerformance Metrics: Evaluate the anomaly detection performanc
 e using metrics such as accuracy\, precision\, recall\, and confusion matr
 ix.\n\n------------------------\nSUBMITTING YOUR SOLUTION\n---------------
