 dp_app3.css"><p><strong>Unit 3 Part 2 Progress</strong></p>\n<p class="kl_
 module_progress_icons" style="display: none\;">Icon Progress Bar/Navigatio
 n (built in browser\, hidden in app)</p>\n<p>&nbsp\;</p>\n<h2>OBJECTIVE</h
 2>\n<p>The objective of this project is to introduce students to the conce
 pts of Gaussian Mixture Models (GMMs) and provide hands-on experience in i
 mplementing them using Python's Scikit-learn library. Students will learn 
 how to preprocess data\, build\, fit\, and evaluate a GMM\, and understand
  the significance of various parameters and their impact on the model's pe
 rformance.</p>\n<p><em><strong>NOTE: </strong>Even though Gaussian Mixture
  Models (GMM) is an unsupervised learning method\, when applied to anomaly
  detection\, it can be treated similarly to a supervised task. After train
 ing the GMM on normal data\, we can use a train-test split to evaluate its
  performance on new data. The model assigns probabilities to each point\, 
 and by setting a threshold on these probabilities\, we can classify points
  as either normal or anomalous. This allows us to evaluate the model using
  traditional classification metrics like precision\, recall\, and the F1-s
 core\, just as we would in a supervised classification task.</em></p>\n<hr
  style="color: #92a2bd\; border: 1px solid\;">\n<h2>INSTRUCTIONS</h2>\n<p>
 <span>Download and use this</span><span>&nbsp\;</span><span class="instruc
