DESCRIPTION:Unit 3 Part 2 Progress\n\nIcon Progress Bar/Navigation (built i
 n browser\, hidden in app)\n\n \n\n---------\nOBJECTIVE\n---------\n\nThe
  goal of this project is to introduce students to the concepts of K-Means 
 Clustering and provide hands-on experience in implementing it using Python
 's Scikit-learn library. Students will learn how to preprocess data\, buil
 d\, fit\, and evaluate a K-Means model\, and understand the significance o
 f various parameters and their impact on the model's performance.\n\n-----
 -------\nINSTRUCTIONS\n------------\n\nDownload and use this [Jupyter Not
 ebook Starter File] (https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/80637
 58?wrap=1) for your solutions to the tasks below. Please complete all of y
 our work for this project in the same Jupyter Notebook file\, which you wi
 ll submit.\n\nThe Dataset\n-----------\n\nDataset Selection: You will be u
 sing the Iris dataset\, which is a well-known dataset in the machine learn
 ing community. It includes various features of iris flowers and their spec
 ies\, making it suitable for clustering. You can access the data from the 
 Scikit-learn's dataset library.\n\niris = load_iris()\n\nDataset Descripti
 on:\n\n* The Iris dataset contains 150 samples with four features each: se
 pal length\, sepal width\, petal length\, and petal width.\n\n* The datase
 t is labeled with three classes: Iris-setosa\, Iris-versicolor\, and Iris-
 virginica.\n\nData Preprocessing\n------------------\n\nLoading Data: Load
  the Iris dataset using Scikit-learn’s load_iris function.\n\nStandardiz
 ation: Standardize the features to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviati
 on of 1 for consistent training. This step is crucial because K-Means uses
  Euclidean distance\, which can be affected by different scales of feature
 s.\n\nBuilding the Model\n------------------\n\nModel Initialization:\n\n*
  Choosing K: Decide on the number of clusters (K). For the Iris dataset\, 
 K=3 is typically used because there are three known classes. Try it out wi
 th a few different values for k\, do some score better than others?\n\n* K
 -Means Initialization: Use the K-Means algorithm from Scikit-learn\, speci
 fying the number of clusters and other parameters such as the random state
  for reproducibility.\n\nModel Fitting: Fit the K-Means model to the stand
 ardized Iris dataset. This process involves the iterative steps of the K-M
 eans algorithm (assignment and update steps) until convergence.\n\nEvaluat
 ing the Model\n--------------------\n\nCluster Assignment: After fitting t
 he model\, obtain the cluster assignments for each data point.\n\nEvaluati
 on Metrics:\n\n* Inertia: Calculate the within-cluster sum of squares (ine
 rtia) to measure how tightly the clusters are packed.\n\n* Silhouette Scor
 e: Use the silhouette score to evaluate the quality of the clusters. This 
 score measures how similar a data point is to its own cluster compared to 
 other clusters.\n\n------------------------\nSUBMITTING YOUR SOLUTION\n---
 ---------------------\n\nSubmit your notebook file. To submit your noteboo
 k\, first clear all the cells (this won't matter too much this time\, but 
 for larger data sets in the future\, it will make the file smaller). Then 
 use the File->Download As->Notebook to obtain the notebook file. Finally\,
  submit the notebook file(s) with your solutions to Canvas.
