DESCRIPTION:Unit 3 Part 3 Progress\n\nIcon Progress Bar/Navigation (built i
 n browser\, hidden in app)\n\n \n\n---------\nOBJECTIVE\n---------\n\nThe
  goal of this project is to introduce students to the concepts of Convolut
 ional Neural Networks (CNNs) and provide hands-on experience in implementi
 ng them using TensorFlow v2. Students will learn to preprocess data\, buil
 d\, fit\, and evaluate a CNN model\, and understand the significance of va
 rious parameters and their impact on the model's performance. This project
  will involve using a unique dataset to classify images of rock\, paper\, 
 and scissors.\n\n------------\nINSTRUCTIONS\n------------\n\nDownload and 
 use this [Jupyter Notebook Starter File] (https://elearning.mines.edu/cou
 rses/76742/files/8063813?wrap=1) for your solutions to the tasks below. Pl
 ease complete all of your work for this project in the same Jupyter Notebo
 ok file\, which you will submit.\n\nThe Dataset\n-----------\n\nDataset Se
 lection: You will be using the Rock-Paper-Scissors image dataset\, which i
 ncludes images of hands showing rock\, paper\, and scissors gestures. This
  dataset is unique and provides a fun and real-world application for image
  classification using CNNs. You can access this dataset from TensorFlow's 
 dataset library.\n\n(train_data\, val_data\, test_data)\, info = tfds.load
 (\n    'rock_paper_scissors'\,\n    split=['train[:80%]'\, 'train[80%:
 90%]'\, 'train[90%:]']\,\n    with_info=True\,\n    as_supervised=True
 \,\n)\n\nDataset Description:\n\n* The Rock-Paper-Scissors dataset contain
 s 2\,892 images divided into three classes: rock\, paper\, and scissors. E
 ach class has around 1\,000 images.\n\n* The images are RGB with a size of
  300x300 pixels.\n\nData Preprocessing\n------------------\n\nLoading Data
 : Load the Rock-Paper-Scissors dataset using TensorFlow Datasets.\n\nData 
 Exploration and Visualization: Produce some visualizations\, statistics\, 
 etc. to gain an understanding for the dataset and what it contains.\n\nDat
 a Augmentation: Apply data augmentation techniques such as rotation\, zoom
 \, and flipping to increase the diversity of the training data.\n\n# Defin
 e data augmentation function\ndef augment(image\, label):\n    image = t
 f.image.resize(image\, [150\, 150])\n    image = tf.image.random_flip_le
 ft_right(image)\n    image = tf.image.random_flip_up_down(image)\n    
 image = tf.image.random_brightness(image\, max_delta=0.3)\n    image = t
 f.image.random_contrast(image\, lower=0.7\, upper=1.3)\n    return image
 \, label\n\nStandardization: Normalize the pixel values to have a mean of 
 0 and a standard deviation of 1 for consistent training.\n\nTrain-Test Spl
 it: Split the dataset into training\, validation\, and testing sets to eva
 luate the model's performance on unseen data.\n\nBuilding the Model\n-----
 -------------\n\nModel Initialization:\n\n* Choosing Hyperparameters: Expl
 ain key hyperparameters such as the number of convolutional layers\, filte
 r sizes\, kernel sizes\, activation functions\, and dropout rates.\n\n* CN
 N Initialization: Use the TensorFlow and Keras libraries to define the CNN
  architecture.\n\nModel Fitting: Fit the CNN model to the preprocessed Roc
 k-Paper-Scissors dataset. Fit for ~10-20 epochs (you can do more but this 
 may take extra time\, remember\, the training may take some time for such 
 a complex model).\n\nEvaluating the Model\n--------------------\n\nPerform
 ance Metrics: Calculate metrics such as accuracy\, precision\, recall\, F1
  score\, and confusion matrix to evaluate the model. These metrics provide
  insights into the model’s predictive performance and its ability to gen
 eralize.\n\n------------------------\nSUBMITTING YOUR SOLUTION\n----------
 --------------\n\nSubmit your notebook file. To submit your notebook\, fir
 st clear all the cells (this won't matter too much this time\, but for lar
 ger data sets in the future\, it will make the file smaller). Then use the
  File->Download As->Notebook to obtain the notebook file. Finally\, submit
  the notebook file(s) with your solutions to Canvas.
