DESCRIPTION:Unit 3 Part 3 Progress\n\nIcon Progress Bar/Navigation (built i
 n browser\, hidden in app)\n\n \n\n---------\nOBJECTIVE\n---------\n\nThe
  objective of this project is to introduce students to the concepts of Art
 ificial Neural Networks (ANNs) and provide hands-on experience in implemen
 ting them using TensorFlow. Students will learn how to preprocess data\, b
 uild\, train\, and evaluate an ANN model on two different types of data (e
 .g.\, image and numerical)\, and understand the significance of various hy
 perparameters and their impact on the model's performance.\n\n------------
 \nINSTRUCTIONS\n------------\n\nDownload and use this [Jupyter Notebook S
 tarter File] (https://elearning.mines.edu/courses/76742/files/8063915?wrap
 =1) for your solutions to the tasks below. Please complete all of your wor
 k for this project in the same Jupyter Notebook file\, which you will subm
 it.\n\nThe Dataset(s)\n--------------\n\nDataset Selection: You will be us
 ing two different types of data (e.g.\, image and numerical). Although the
  datasets and preprocessing tasks differ\, you will be performing the same
  steps for building and evaluating your models. You can access both of the
 se datasets from the Scikit-learn's dataset library.\n\n* Part 1: CIFAR-10
  Dataset - Image Based\n\n(X_train\, y_train)\, (X_test\, y_test) = cifar1
 0.load_data()\n\n* Part 2: California Housing Dataset - Numerical Based\n\
 ndata = fetch_california_housing()\n\nDataset Descriptions:\n\n* Part 1: C
 IFAR-10 Dataset - Image Based\n\nThe CIFAR-10 dataset is a widely used ben
 chmark dataset in machine learning and computer vision. It consists of 60\
 ,000 color images in 10 different classes\, with 6\,000 images per class. 
 The dataset is divided into 50\,000 training images and 10\,000 test image
 s.\n\n* Part 2: California Housing Dataset - Numerical Based\n\nThe Califo
 rnia Housing dataset is a classic dataset used for regression tasks. It co
 nsists of information collected from the 1990 California census\, which ai
 ms to predict the median house value in various districts based on several
  features.\n\nData Preprocessing\n------------------\n\n* Part 1: CIFAR-10
  Dataset - Image Based\n\nLoading Data: Load the Iris dataset using Sciki
 t-learn’s cifar10.load_data() function.\n\nNormalization: Normalize the 
 pixel values of images to a range of 0 to 1 to ensure uniformity and faste
 r convergence during training.\n\nOne-Hot Encoding: Convert categorical la
 bels into binary class matrices (one-hot encoding) to be used with neural 
 networks.\n\n* Part 2: California Housing Dataset - Numerical Based\n\nLoa
 ding Data: Load the Iris dataset using Scikit-learn’s fetch_california_
 housing() function.\n\nHandling Missing Values: Identify and handle any mi
 ssing values in the dataset (e.g.\, using mean or median imputation).\n\nF
 eature Scaling: Standardize the features to have a mean of 0 and a standar
 d deviation of 1 for consistent training.\n\nTrain-Test Split: Split the d
 ataset into training and testing sets to evaluate the model's performance 
 on unseen data.\n\nBuilding the Model\n------------------\n\nModel Archite
 cture:\n\n* Input Layer: Define the input shape based on the dataset (e.g.
 \, 32x32x3 for CIFAR-10\, number of features for California Housing Prices
 ).\n\n* Hidden Layers: Add several hidden layers with a specified number o
 f neurons and activation functions (e.g.\, ReLU). Experiment with differen
 t architectures.\n\n* Output Layer: Define the output layer with an approp
 riate activation function (e.g.\, softmax for classification\, linear for 
 regression).\n\nCompilation:\n\n* Loss Function: Choose a suitable loss fu
 nction based on the task (e.g.\, categorical crossentropy for classificati
 on\, mean squared error for regression).\n\n* Optimizer: Select an optimiz
 er like Adam or SGD to minimize the loss function during training.\n\n* Me
 trics: Define evaluation metrics to monitor the training process (e.g.\, a
 ccuracy for classification\, mean absolute error for regression).\n\nModel
  Training:\n\n* Epochs: Set the number of epochs\, which determine how man
 y times the model will iterate over the entire training dataset.\n\n* Batc
 h Size: Choose a batch size that specifies the number of samples processed
  before updating the model’s parameters.\n\n* Validation Split: Use a po
 rtion of the training data as a validation set to monitor the model's perf
 ormance during training and avoid overfitting.\n\n* Monitoring Training: T
 rack the training and validation accuracy/loss to observe the model's lear
 ning progress and detect any signs of overfitting or underfitting.\n\nEval
 uating the Model\n--------------------\n\nTesting Data: Evaluate the model
 's performance on the testing dataset to assess its generalization capabil
 ity.\n\nPerformance Metrics: Calculate relevant metrics to quantify the mo
 del's performance\, such as accuracy\, precision\, and recall for classifi
 cation tasks\, and mean absolute error\, mean squared error\, and root mea
 n squared error for regression tasks.\n\n------------------------\nSUBMITT
 ING YOUR SOLUTION\n------------------------\n\nSubmit your notebook file. 
 To submit your notebook\, first clear all the cells (this won't matter too
  much this time\, but for larger data sets in the future\, it will make th
 e file smaller). Then use the File->Download As->Notebook to obtain the no
 tebook file. Finally\, submit the notebook file(s) with your solutions to 
 Canvas.
