CLASS:PUBLIC
DESCRIPTION:Unit 6 Progress\n\nIcon Progress Bar/Navigation (built in brows
 er\, hidden in app)\n\n \n\n---------\nOBJECTIVE\n---------\n\nThe overal
 l objective of this project is to package your work by applying the concep
 ts learned during the data storytelling and advanced visualization stages 
 of our workflow.\n\n------------\nINSTRUCTIONS\n------------\n\nSelect TWO
  (2) of your favorite projects\, each representing a different type of mod
 el we studied during the model selection portion of the class (e.g.\, one 
 clustering and one instance-based). This can be new ones or the same proje
 cts selected in the Results and Evaluation Project.\n\n* Apply data storyt
 elling techniques\, including advanced or explanatory visualizations\, to 
 these projects. In the next section\, you will find recommendations for vi
 sualizations you can use for each model.\n\n* For each model you selected\
 , prepare a detailed report in the form of a Jupyter Notebook File (or pdf
  report) summarizing the project\, including the following sections:\n\n* 
 Audience: Before starting you will need to choose who your presentation wi
 ll be aimed at. Please provide a paragraph that details who the stakeholde
 rs are\, what they may know or not know and how you will tailor your prese
 ntation to their needs. Some ideas are data scientist\, students\, manager
 s\, C-suite executives\, general public\, etc.\n\n* Introduction: Provide 
 a brief overview of the problem and the chosen dataset.\n\n* Data Preproce
 ssing: Describe the data preprocessing steps\, including loading\, data ex
 ploration and visualization\, handling missing values\, encoding categoric
 al variables\, feature engineering\, and standardizing the data.\n\n* Mode
 l Architecture: Explain the model and the selected parameters.\n\n* Traini
 ng and Evaluation: Summarize the training process\, the evaluation metrics
  used\, and the results obtained.\n\n* Parameter Tuning: Discuss the exper
 iments conducted to find the optimal hyperparameters and their outcomes.\n
 \n* Visualizations (see below for recommendations for visualizations you c
 an use for each model).\n\n* Conclusion: Share insights gained from the pr
 oject and potential improvements for future work.\n\n------------------\nS
 ELECT YOUR MODELS\n------------------\n\nFor each model we have studied\, 
 we have provided recommended visualizations you can use. If you discover a
 dditional or alternative ideas\, feel free to include them in your analysi
 s.\n\nLinear Regression\n-----------------\n\nLinear Regression\n---------
 --------\n\n* Residual Plot: Visualize the residual plot to understand the
  model’s performance in detail\, including how well the model captures t
 he patterns in the data.\n\n* Prediction Plot: Plot the predicted vs. actu
 al values to visualize how well the model predicts the target variable.\n\
 n* Learning Curves: Plot learning curves to show the model’s performance
  (e.g.\, MSE) as a function of the number of training samples. This helps 
 in understanding how the model’s performance improves with more data.\n\
 nK-Nearest Neighbors\n-------------------\n\nK-Nearest Neighbors\n--------
 -----------\n\n* Confusion Matrix: Visualize the confusion matrix to under
 stand the model’s performance in detail\, including how many instances w
 ere correctly or incorrectly classified for each class.\n\n* Learning Curv
 es: Plot learning curves to show the model’s performance (e.g.\, accurac
 y) as a function of the number of training samples. This helps in understa
 nding how the model’s performance improves with more data.\n\nSupport Ve
 ctor Machines\n-----------------------\n\nSupport Vector Machines\n-------
 ----------------\n\n* Confusion Matrix: Visualize the confusion matrix to 
 understand the model’s performance in detail\, including how many instan
 ces were correctly or incorrectly classified for each class.\n\n* Decision
  Boundary: Visualize the decision boundary (if applicable) to understand h
 ow the SVM separates the different classes.\n\n* Learning Curves: Plot lea
 rning curves to show the model’s performance (e.g.\, accuracy) as a func
 tion of the number of training samples. This helps in understanding how th
 e model’s performance improves with more data. Using sklearn or another 
 library:\nhttps://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/model_selection/pl
 ot_learning_curve.html \n\nDecision Trees\n--------------\n\nDecision Tre
 es\n--------------\n\n* Confusion Matrix: Visualize the confusion matrix t
 o understand the model’s performance in detail\, including how many inst
 ances were correctly or incorrectly classified for each class.\n\n* Featur
 e Importance Plot: Create a bar plot of feature importances to visualize w
 hich features are most influential in the model’s predictions.\n\n# Feat
 ure importance for the base decision tree\nimportances = dt.feature_import
 ances_\nindices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]\nfeature_names = df.column
 s[:-1]\n\n* Learning Curves: Plot learning curves to show the model’s pe
 rformance (e.g.\, accuracy) as a function of the number of training sample
 s. This helps in understanding how the model’s performance improves with
  more data.\n\n* Plot Best Tree: Using sklearn or another library\, plot t
 he decision tree.\n\n* https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/s
 klearn.tree.plot_tree.html \n\nRandom Forests\n--------------\n\nRandom F
 orests\n--------------\n\n* Confusion Matrix: Visualize the confusion matr
 ix to understand the model’s performance in detail\, including how many 
 instances were correctly or incorrectly classified for each class.\n\n* Fe
 ature Importance Plot: Create a bar plot of feature importances to visuali
 ze which features are most influential in the model’s predictions.\n\n# 
 Get feature importances\nimportances = rf.feature_importances_\nindices = 
 np.argsort(importances)[::-1]\nfeature_names = df.columns[:-1]\n\n* Learni
 ng Curves: Plot learning curves to show the model’s performance (e.g.\, 
 accuracy) as a function of the number of training samples. This helps in u
 nderstanding how the model’s performance improves with more data.\n\nk-M
 eans Clustering\n------------------\n\nk-Means Clustering\n---------------
 ---\n\n* Scatter Plot: Create a scatter plot of the data points with color
 s indicating their cluster assignments. Highlight the cluster centroids on
  the plot.\n\n* Pair Plot: For multi-dimensional data like the Iris datase
 t\, use pair plots to visualize the clustering results across different fe
 ature combinations.\n\n* Centroids: Plot the centroids of the clusters to 
 show the center of each cluster.\n\n* Sources: https://scikit-learn.org/st
 able/modules/generated/sklearn.cluster.KMeans.html \n\nGaussian Mixture M
 odel\n----------------------\n\nGaussian Mixture Model\n------------------
 ----\n\nAnomaly Detection Visualization:\n\n* Real-World Data: Plot the di
 stribution of anomaly scores and visualize the detected anomalies.\n\n* Vi
 sualize the clusters and their distributions using scatter plots and conto
 ur plots.\n\nArtificial Neural Networks\n--------------------------\n\nArt
 ificial Neural Networks\n--------------------------\n\n* Accuracy/Loss Plo
 ts: Plot the training and validation accuracy/loss over epochs to visualiz
 e the model's learning process.\n\n* Interpretation: Analyze the plots to 
 understand the model's behavior (e.g.\, detecting overfitting\, underfitti
 ng).\n\nConvolutional Neural Networks\n-----------------------------\n\nCo
 nvolutional Neural Networks\n-----------------------------\n\n* Confusion 
 Matrix: Visualize the confusion matrix to understand the model’s perform
 ance in detail\, including how many instances were correctly or incorrectl
 y classified for each class.\n\n* Loss and Accuracy Curves: Plot the loss 
 and accuracy curves to visualize the model’s training process and detect
  any signs of overfitting or underfitting.\n\n------------------------\nSU
 BMITTING YOUR SOLUTION\n------------------------\n\nSubmit your notebook f
 ile(s) or pdf(s). To submit your notebook\, first clear all the cells (thi
 s won't matter too much this time\, but for larger data sets in the future
 \, it will make the file smaller). Then use the File->Download As->Noteboo
 k to obtain the notebook file. Finally\, submit the notebook file(s) with 
 your solutions to Canvas.
